Codeforces Problem : Eugene and Array :
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
C. Eugene and an array
time limit per test1.5 seconds
memory limit per test256 megabytes
inputstandard input
outputstandard output
Eugene likes working with arrays. And today he needs your help in solving one challenging task.

An array ğ‘ is a subarray of an array ğ‘ if ğ‘ can be obtained from ğ‘ by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements from the beginning and several (possibly, zero or all) elements from the end.

Let's call a nonempty array good if for every nonempty subarray of this array, sum of the elements of this subarray is nonzero. For example, array [âˆ’1,2,âˆ’3] is good, as all arrays [âˆ’1], [âˆ’1,2], [âˆ’1,2,âˆ’3], [2], [2,âˆ’3], [âˆ’3] have nonzero sums of elements. However, array [âˆ’1,2,âˆ’1,âˆ’3] isn't good, as his subarray [âˆ’1,2,âˆ’1] has sum of elements equal to 0.

Help Eugene to calculate the number of nonempty good subarrays of a given array ğ‘.

Input
The first line of the input contains a single integer ğ‘› (1â‰¤ğ‘›â‰¤2Ã—105)  â€” the length of array ğ‘.

The second line of the input contains ğ‘› integers ğ‘1,ğ‘2,â€¦,ğ‘ğ‘› (âˆ’109â‰¤ğ‘ğ‘–â‰¤109)  â€” the elements of ğ‘.

Output
Output a single integer  â€” the number of good subarrays of ğ‘.

Examples
inputCopy
3
1 2 -3
outputCopy
5
inputCopy
3
41 -41 41
outputCopy
3
Note
In the first sample, the following subarrays are good: [1], [1,2], [2], [2,âˆ’3], [âˆ’3]. However, the subarray [1,2,âˆ’3] isn't good, as its subarray [1,2,âˆ’3] has sum of elements equal to 0.

In the second sample, three subarrays of size 1 are the only good subarrays. At the same time, the subarray [41,âˆ’41,41] isn't good, as its subarray [41,âˆ’41] has sum of elements equal to 0.



solution:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Let's solve this problem in ğ‘‚(ğ‘›2Ã—ğ‘™ğ‘œğ‘”(ğ‘›))for now.

Note that if the subarray [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—] is good, then the subarray [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—âˆ’1] is also good, and if the subset [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—] is not good, then the subarray [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—+1] is not good either. Then for each left border ğ‘ğ‘– we want to find the rightmost border ğ‘ğ‘— such that [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—] is good and add to the answer ğ‘—âˆ’ğ‘–+1 (subarrays [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—],[ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—âˆ’1],...,[ğ‘ğ‘–]) [1]. Let's denote the rightmost border ğ‘— for border ğ‘– as ğ‘…(ğ‘–).

Let's calculate the prefix-sum of the array ğ‘ƒ.

ğ‘ƒ0=0,ğ‘ƒğ‘–=ğ‘1+..+ğ‘ğ‘–,1â‰¤ğ‘–â‰¤ğ‘›.

Note that a subset of [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—] has a zero sum iff ğ‘ƒğ‘–âˆ’1=ğ‘ƒğ‘—. Then the subset [ğ‘ğ‘–,...,ğ‘ğ‘—] is a good iff sum of prefixes [ğ‘ƒğ‘–âˆ’1,...,ğ‘ƒğ‘—] has no duplicates [2].

Using [1] and [2], we can simply iterate over ğ‘– from 0 to ğ‘› and over ğ‘— from ğ‘– to ğ‘› and count the set of prefix sums [ğ‘ƒğ‘–,...,ğ‘ƒğ‘—]. The first moment ğ‘—0 when this set contains duplicates gives us the rightmost border ğ‘—0âˆ’1, and we add (ğ‘—0âˆ’1)âˆ’ğ‘– (no +1, because it is an array of prefix sums) to answer.

To improve this solution to ğ‘‚(ğ‘›Ã—ğ‘™ğ‘œğ‘”(ğ‘›)), we need to note that ğ‘…(ğ‘–) is monotonous over ğ‘–. Now we can iterate over ğ‘– from 0 to ğ‘› and over ğ‘— from ğ‘…(ğ‘–âˆ’1) to ğ‘› uses a set of prefix sums from the previous iteration. Thus we have a solution ğ‘‚(ğ‘›Ã—ğ‘™ğ‘œğ‘”(ğ‘›)), because ğ‘— points to each element of the array exactly once.

If you code in C++, it is important not to use std:: unordered_set in this task, but use std::set. One of the participants hacked the solution using std:: unordered_set, using collisions in this structure. I highly recommend you to read this blog for more info https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/62393.

Final time complexity: ğ‘‚(ğ‘›Ã—ğ‘™ğ‘œğ‘”(ğ‘›))
Solution C++
#include <bits/stdc++.h>

using namespace std;


int main() {
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<long long> prefix(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        int x; cin >> x;
        prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + x;
    }
    int begin = 0, end = 0;
    long long ans = 0;
    set<long long> s = {0};
    while(begin < n) {
        while(end < n && !s.count(prefix[end + 1])) {
            ++end;
            s.insert(prefix[end]);
        }
        ans += end - begin;
        s.erase(prefix[begin]);
        ++begin;
    }
    cout << ans << endl;
}
